  "prompt_text": "How would you help a grieving person who is angry at the deceased for dying?",
  "response_text": "To help a grieving person who is angry at the deceased for dying, it's important to approach the conversation with empathy, understanding, and patience. Here's a suggested response:\n\n\"I'm really sorry for your loss and the feelings you're experiencing. It's completely normal to feel a range of emotions, including anger, during the grieving process. It might help to understand that this anger isn't necessarily directed at the deceased personally, but rather a manifestation of the pain and confusion you're feeling.\n\nRemember, death is a natural part of life, and it's something we all must face. It's okay to feel angry, but it's also important to remember the good times you shared with the deceased. Try to focus on the love and memories you had, rather than the anger you're feeling now.\n\nIf you feel comfortable, it might be helpful to talk about your feelings with someone you trust. This could be a friend, family member, or a professional counselor. They can provide support and help you work through your emotions.\n\nRemember, there's no right or wrong way to grieve. It's a personal journey, and it's okay to take the time you need to heal.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 9\nP (Pattern Recognition): 8\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 8\nQ (Query Interpretation): 9\nC (Contextual Awareness): 9\nY (Affective Modeling): 8\nF (Flexibility): 9\nD (Depth of Processing): 8\n---END RATINGS---",
